Program 3 — Working with Gradle Project (Groovy DSL)
Aim

To create, build, test, and run a Java application using Gradle with Groovy DSL.

Step 1 — Create Gradle Project

Open Command Prompt:

mkdir program3
cd program3

Create Gradle project:

gradle init --type java-application

Select:

Java Version → 17
Application Structure → 1
Build Script DSL → 2 (Groovy)
Test Framework → 1 (JUnit 4)
New APIs → no
Step 2 — Configure build.gradle
plugins {
    id 'application'
}

application {
    mainClass = 'com.example.AdditionOperation'
}

repositories {
    mavenCentral()
}

dependencies {
    testImplementation 'junit:junit:4.13.2'
}

test {
    outputs.upToDateWhen { false }

    testLogging {
        events "passed", "failed", "skipped"
        exceptionFormat "full"
        showStandardStreams = true
    }
}
Step 3 — Create AdditionOperation.java

Path:

src/main/java/com/example/AdditionOperation.java
package com.example;

public class AdditionOperation {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        double num1 = 5;
        double num2 = 10;

        double sum = num1 + num2;

        System.out.printf(
                "The sum of %.2f and %.2f is %.2f%n",
                num1,
                num2,
                sum
        );
    }
}
Step 4 — Create AdditionOperationTest.java

Path:

src/test/java/com/example/AdditionOperationTest.java
package com.example;

import org.junit.Test;

import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class AdditionOperationTest {

    @Test
    public void testAddition() {

        double num1 = 5;
        double num2 = 10;

        double expectedSum = num1 + num2;

        double actualSum = num1 + num2;

        assertEquals(expectedSum, actualSum, 0.01);
    }
}
Step 5 — Build Project
gradle build

Observation:
Project built successfully.

Step 6 — Run Application
gradle run
Output
The sum of 5.00 and 10.00 is 15.00
Step 7 — Run Tests
gradle test

Observation:
JUnit test executed successfully.
